13. 1100 plenae 1100 adeo timendae. This criticism is perfectly just3 see Pressense iv. 369 ff. The highest standard of Pagan morality, as exhibited in the Stoicism of Seneca, was impotent in results. Heathen ethics neither penetrated to the conscience and soul nor inspired dread in those who despised them; they were neither com- plete nor sanotioned by penalties ; and their failure is a fact witnessed to by the historians and satirists of the empire. Comp. J uven. i. 147 ff. ; Clem. Alex. Paed. iii. 3; Cyprian. Ep. 1 ad Donat. On Christian docti-Ine as the great motive to Christian action see Mozley’s Bampt. tect. vii. pp. 136 ff.
